<p><span class="newthought">In this first post</span> <label for="sn-id-whatever" class="margin-toggle sidenote-number"></label><input type="checkbox" id="sn-id-whatever" class="margin-toggle" /><span class="sidenote">If youâ€™d like to know the general idea behind this series of blog posts, check out the <a href="/index.html">introduction</a> I wrote </span> Iâ€™m starting at a super-basic level with the math-elements because the main intention is to get my head used to the method of chunking much advocated in <a href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Mind-Numbers-Science-Flunked-Algebra-ebook/dp/B00G3L19ZU">Oakleyâ€™s â€œA Mind for Numbersâ€</a>. My aim being that the method, as well as the chunks it produces, will embed nicely before I start to use either in anger.</p>

<p>The following is based on problems 1 to 24 from <a href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Algebra-I-M-Gelfand/dp/0817636773">Gelfandâ€™s â€œAlgebraâ€</a>.</p>

<p>Lots of the subsequent posts will be taken from chunks derived from that book too.  You can tell which because itâ€™ll be flagged in the title, and a tag (â€œ<a href="/tags.html#gelfand-ref">gelfand</a>â€).</p>

<h2 id="chunking-the-standard-addition-algorithm">Chunking the <em>Standard Addition Algorithm</em></h2>
<p><span class="newthought">Gelfand kicks off</span>  with the <em>Standard Addition Algorithm</em>. It will surely be familiar to everyone from their elementary mathematics.  Itâ€™s described nicely <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_arithmetic#Addition_algorithm">over at wikipedia</a> so I wonâ€™t repeat it here.</p>

<p>What follows is a tidied up<label for="sn-id-whatever" class="margin-toggle sidenote-number"></label><input type="checkbox" id="sn-id-whatever" class="margin-toggle" /><span class="sidenote">I did them initially using pen and paper. </span> verison of my notes from working through problem 2 (pp. 4) using the chunking approach from Oakley (chapter 7, â€œHow to Build a Powerful Chunkâ€).</p>

<p>In the course of doing this I noted some tricks.  It turns out that the tricks are one of the keys to all this.  I have <em>highlighted</em> them here (and explained them a little more in a later section).  This is a theme which Iâ€™ll keep returning to throughout these posts.  Having an embedded set of tricks, and patterns to use to trigger them is key to math-success.</p>

<h3 id="step-1-work-a-problem-all-the-way-through-on-paper">Step 1: â€œWork a problem all the way through on paperâ€</h3>
<p>(Youâ€™ll just have to trust me when I say I did this.)</p>

<h3 id="step-2-work-it-through-again-paying-attention-to-the-key-processes">Step 2: â€œWork it through again, paying attention to the key processesâ€</h3>
<p>The steps I followed were as youâ€™d expect from the worked solution in the book.</p>

<p>Firstly, <em>eliminate the impossible</em> - what are the possible values for the left-most <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">A</script></span>?</p>

<p>Secondly, start from zero and <em>work up, one step at a time</em>:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Can it be <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">0</script></span>? No.</li>
  <li>Can it be <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1</script></span>? Yes.</li>
  <li>Can it be <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">2</script></span>? The maximum possible value is <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">9 + 8 + 1 = 18</script></span>. So no, it canâ€™t.</li>
  <li>Can it be <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex"> \gt 2</script></span>? No. So that means <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">A</script></span> can only be <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1</script></span>.</li>
</ul>

<p>Now is a great point to pause, and fill in what we know so far, in order to get a fresh look at things. Our problem now looks like this:</p>

<div class="mathblock"><script type="math/tex; mode=display">\begin{matrix} \phantom0 \phantom0 \texttt{1} \texttt{1} \texttt{1} \\ \underline{\texttt{+}\texttt{ }\texttt{ }\texttt{B}\texttt{B}\texttt{B}}  \\ \phantom0 \texttt{111C} \end{matrix}</script></div>

<p>Now we can keep going. Thirdly, <em>eliminate the impossible (again)</em>:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Do we have a carry from the rightmost <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1 + B</script></span>?  We must do because the next-left column has a different result value.</li>
  <li>Therefore <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">B</script></span> can only be <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">9</script></span> (because <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1 + 9  \gt 9</script></span> which we need to have a carry).</li>
</ul>

<p>Finally, work back up, which means <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">C = 0</script></span>.</p>

<p>And so weâ€™re done, giving us the following solution:</p>

<div class="mathblock"><script type="math/tex; mode=display">\begin{matrix} \phantom 0 \phantom0 \texttt{1} \texttt{1} \texttt{1} \\ \underline{\texttt{+}\texttt{ }\texttt{ }\texttt{9}\texttt{9}\texttt{9}}  \\ \phantom0 \texttt{1110} \end{matrix}</script></div>

<h3 id="step-3-take-a-break">Step 3: â€œTake a breakâ€</h3>
<p>Basically I stopped at this point and went on to the next set of problems. (The ones we get onto later in this post.)</p>

<h3 id="step-4-sleep">Step 4: â€œSleepâ€</h3>
<p>This involved working each and every of the steps I described above.</p>

<h3 id="step-5-do-another-repetition">Step 5: â€œDo another repetitionâ€</h3>
<p>First thing next morning, I worked the problem yet again, following each and every one of the original steps.  Oakley states â€œyour understanding should be deeperâ€ and sheâ€™s right - the repetitions (and breaks) meant that now certain visual elements of both the problem and the solution came to me.  Iâ€™ve captured these realisations below in the â€œTricks Arisingâ€ section below as <em>â€œmany patterns you can spot visuallyâ€</em> and <em>â€œhave lots of space around your problems as you workâ€</em></p>

<h3 id="step-6-add-another-problem">Step 6: â€œAdd another problemâ€</h3>
<p>At this point I kept on going, launching into the Multiplication problem that is the subject of the second half of this post.</p>

<h3 id="step-7--do-active-repetitions">Step 7:  â€œDo â€˜activeâ€™ repetitionsâ€</h3>
<p>I take a walk out at lunch, and drive to and from work which takes 40 - 60 minutes each way, so on all of these occasions I repeated the solution steps to myself, making sure I visualised everything fully.</p>

<p>And thatâ€™s it.  It felt like it worked really well.  It didnâ€™t feel self-patronising either.  By focussing on something mathematically simple, I just freed up the mental space needed to grokk Oakleyâ€™s process itself, and how it felt as I followed it.  Not only that, I also got a far better, and more explicit understanding of the nuances and patterns inherant in the <em>Standard Addition Algorithm</em>.</p>

<h3 id="addition-patterns">Addition Patterns</h3>
<p>The end result of the working through of this problem following the chunking method was not only the above solution, but also an awareness of the following patterns in the <em>Standard Addition Algorithm</em>:</p>

<p>In any column, the sum-value is equal to the remainder of (the total of all values above it + carry-value) <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">/ 10</script></span>;</p>

<p>In the right-hand column, there is no carry-value (or the carry-value is equivalent to <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">0</script></span>);</p>

<p>If there are only two values to sum, then the max carry-value is <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1</script></span> (as <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">9 + 9 + 1 = 19</script></span>);</p>

<p>If there is a sum-value which has no values above it, then it must be the same as the carry-value from the column to itâ€™s right;</p>

<p>If two columns have the same values, but different sum-values, then the difference is solely a result of the carry values.</p>

<h2 id="the-multiplication-algorithm-for-multi-digit-factors">The Multiplication Algorithm for Multi-Digit Factors</h2>
<p><span class="newthought">Next up</span>  were problems relating to the <em>Multiplication Algorithm for Multi-Digit Factors</em>. This was unfamiliar to me.  It too is described nicely <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_arithmetic#Multiplication_algorithm_for_multi-digit_factors">over at wikipedia</a>.</p>

<p>From this point onwards Iâ€™ll not write out in detail my chunking-led approach to things (thereâ€™s little point) but following it further embedded the tricks Iâ€™d already spotted, as well as making the following patterns evident to me.</p>

<h3 id="multiplication-patterns">Multiplication Patterns</h3>

<p>The result is the same, no matter in what order you place the terms;</p>

<p>Repetition patterns featuring one of the terms appear in the product when the other term comprises one or more repetitions of <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1</script></span> followed by a number of <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">0</script></span>. The number of <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">0</script></span>s must be equal to the number of numerals in the other term minus <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1</script></span>;</p>

<p>A <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1</script></span> at a given position in the first term has the effect of taking the second term and shifting it to the left.  The magnitude of this shift is the same as the power of ten of the position of the <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1</script></span> in the first term;</p>

<p>The second impact is of addition, which can be seen using the <em>Standard Addition Algorithm</em> (see above), and here the same patterns again apply.</p>

<h2 id="the-long-division-algorithm">The Long-Division Algorithm</h2>
<blockquote>
  <p>â€œIn mathematics, especially in elementary arithmetic, division is an arithmetic operation which is the inverse of multiplication.â€
(from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_arithmetic#Division">wikipedia</a>)</p>
</blockquote>

<p><span class="newthought">Note, this isnâ€™t,</span>  in my experience, strictly speaking 100% true.  Itâ€™ll help you get along for now, but bear in mind that in time (and weâ€™ll get to it in later posts) youâ€™ll see some differences.<label for="sn-id-whatever" class="margin-toggle sidenote-number"></label><input type="checkbox" id="sn-id-whatever" class="margin-toggle" /><span class="sidenote">For example multiplying by zero (result: zero) and dividing by zero (result: undefined). </span></p>

<p>There is yet again a well-established algorithm for handling division in the positional number systems called â€œlong divisionâ€.  Itâ€™s explained well in the wikipedia page linked above.</p>

<h3 id="long-division-patterns-and-cyclic-numbers">Long-Division Patterns and Cyclic Numbers</h3>
<p>Gelfand stops at one point to point out the existence of so-called â€œcyclic numbersâ€.  There is a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclic_number">whole load of detail</a> on this which he doesnâ€™t go into, and there is no need to know any more about them than notice their existence and the circumstances under which they arise.  What is important here (I now realise on second reading) is that my previously mentioned â€œpattern-awarenessâ€ can help you notice a lot of things.  Iâ€™m going to go into this a little more in the next section.  One thing I want to note here however is that, as a visual thinker, I was happy to see just how much physically â€œseeingâ€ patterns on the page in front of you was a valuable skill.</p>

<h2 id="tricks-arising">Tricks Arising</h2>
<p><span class="newthought">Iâ€™ve alluded to â€œtricksâ€</span>  that I learned as I went.  It seems to me that these are going to become more and more key as I progress through my maths journey.</p>

<p>The ones I have so far are:</p>

<h3 id="you-can-spot-many-patterns-visually">You can spot many patterns visually</h3>
<p>Take time to lay out your problem in a way which is clear.  Areas which are not symmetrical after you have done this may be worthy of attention</p>

<h3 id="have-lots-of-space-around-your-problems-as-you-work">Have lots of space around your problems as you work</h3>
<p>This feels<label for="sn-id-whatever" class="margin-toggle sidenote-number"></label><input type="checkbox" id="sn-id-whatever" class="margin-toggle" /><span class="sidenote">To me at least. </span> as if it creates a corresponding mental<label for="sn-id-whatever" class="margin-toggle sidenote-number"></label><input type="checkbox" id="sn-id-whatever" class="margin-toggle" /><span class="sidenote">Working memory? </span> space.  It also helps when trying to spot visual elements.</p>

<h3 id="eliminate-the-impossible">Eliminate the impossible</h3>
<p>What <em>canâ€™t</em> happen?  This shrinks the problem space, and gives you less to think about, allowing you to focus.</p>

<h3 id="break-the-problem-into-smaller-more-manageable-pieces">Break the problem into smaller, more manageable pieces</h3>
<p>Then work back up to the complete solution - again, simplify.</p>

<h3 id="start-from-zero-and-then-work-up-one-step-at-a-time">Start from zero, and then work up, one step at a time</h3>
<p>Self-explanatory this one really.</p>

<h3 id="if-the-order-of-terms-makes-no-difference-to-the-result-use-this-to-your-advantage">If the order of terms makes no difference to the result, use this to your advantage</h3>
<p>Are you going to draw out {$ m %}517 \times 1001&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/span&gt; or <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1001 \times 517</script></span>?  Pick the one which makes things easier.</p>

