<h3 id="undefined">â€œUndefinedâ€</h3>
<p>This is the first time we hit the phrase â€œundefinedâ€ - still in our case in the realm of arithmetic. In this case it is when we try and divide a real number by <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">0</script></span>.  There is also the case of <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">0^0</script></span>.  In both cases these are circumstances when we know what we are trying to do doesnt make sense, so there is no â€œanswerâ€, so the expression is â€œundefindedâ€.</p>

<h3 id="rational-real-and-irrational-numbers">Rational, Real and Irrational Numbers</h3>
<p>From <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number">wikipedia</a>:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€œRational numbers are any number that can be expressed as the quotient or fraction <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">\frac{p}{q}</script></span> of two integers, a numerator <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">p</script></span> and a non-zero denominator <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">q</script></span>. Since <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">q</script></span> may be equal to <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">1</script></span>, every integer is a rational number.â€</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Again from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number">wikipedia</a>:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€œReal numbers are values that represent a quantity along a line.  The real numbers include all the rational numbers such as the integer <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">-5</script></span> and the fraction <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">\frac{4}{3}</script></span>, and all the irrational numbers such as <span>â€‹<script type="math/tex">\sqrt[2]{2}</script></span>â€</p>
</blockquote>
